## How to resolve

1. Open each conflicted file listed above.
2. Resolve every conflict-marker region thoughtfully, preserving the intent of
   BOTH the feature branch and `{{ target }}`. Never delete one side blindly.
3. Remove every `<<<<<<<`, `=======` and `>>>>>>>` marker line, so each file is
   left as valid, self-consistent content.

## Hard rules

- DO NOT run any git command. Ralph Workflow stages the resolved files and
  {% if replaying_commit_sha %}continues the rebase{% else %}creates the merge commit{% endif %} itself. You only edit file contents. Git is
  denied to this session by the exec policy, so attempting it wastes the round.
- Do not commit, merge, rebase, abort, switch branches, or move any ref.
- Do not modify ANY file that is not listed under "Conflicted files" above.
  Not a neighbouring module, not a test, not an import, not a formatting nit.
  If the resolved code needs a change elsewhere, leave it: that belongs to a
  later run, not to this one.
{% if replaying_commit_sha %}- Ralph Workflow re-reads the worktree after you return. An edit to ANY tracked
  path that is not listed above REJECTS the whole resolution and aborts the
  rebase, discarding your work on the listed files too.
{% endif %}- A leftover conflict marker in ANY listed file REJECTS the whole resolution
  and {% if replaying_commit_sha %}aborts the rebase{% else %}aborts the merge{% endif %}. Ralph Workflow re-scans every listed path
  textually after you return; your own report is never the evidence.

## Completion contract

